"&#xa0;\n              \nWritten evidence to the Enquiry into Democracy and Development in Burma, submitted by the Burma Relief CentreSummaryThis submission by Burma Relief Centre, an NGO with 25 years’ experience in capacity building of civil society and currently receiving DFID support through Christian Aid, contains the following key points:\n-\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nTo enable them to raise community concerns and input policy recommendations into political negotiations so that just, sustainable solutions can be achieved to end the conflict.   \n-\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nTo ensure that humanitarian needs in these conflict areas continue to be met, and existing community social service structures are built upon and not ignored and replaced. \n&#xa0;\nDetailed submission &#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\na)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nAbility to address critical health needs in remote conflict areas. In 2012, indigenous health organizations reached a target population over half a million in conflict affected areas of Burma, and trained almost 3,000 community health workers. \nb)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nPromotion of women’s rights among ethnic communities which are traditionally extremely patriarchal. This has included extensive programming against sexual and gender based violence, including documentation and advocacy against the Burmese military’s use of rape as a weapon of war. \nc)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nDevelopment of a broad media network in the ethnic states, enabling access to information for remote marginalized communities in their own languages, and providing unique reporting on the ongoing peace process.  \nd)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nWidespread community awareness of the need for environmental protection and sustainable development, which has led to the stopping of controversial development projects, such as the \nMyitsone\n dam on the Irrawaddy river in 2011, and the \nTamanthi\n dam on the Chindwin river in 2013. \ne)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nDevelopment of grassroots ethnic farmers’ networks to address issues of widespread\n land grabbing. \nf)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nDevelopment of inter-ethnic alliances in many sectors, which are promoting ethnic reconciliation, for example the Women’s League of Burma, Burma Rivers Network, Burma News International, Ethnic Community Development Forum. \n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n The need to support ethnic civil society to promote sustainable peace&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nThe need to support ethnic civil society to build on and develop social services in their areas&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nOctober 2013\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n Documentation by women’s organizations can be seen on the website of the Women’s League of Burma:  \nwww.womenofburma.org\n \n See the website of Burma News International: \nwww.bnionline.net\n,\n \nand \nwww.mmpeacemonitor.org\n&#xa0;\n See: \nhttp://www.shanhumanrights.org/index.php?option=com_content&amp;view=article&amp;id=345:27-august-2012&amp;catid=75:action-updae\n"